Note:
Runa Standard Library: Geometry

Production-grade geometric computations with 2D/3D shapes, transformations,
collision detection, and advanced computational geometry algorithms.
:End Note

Import "math/core" as Core

Note: 2D Point and Vector Types
Type called "Point2D":
    x as Number
    y as Number

Type called "Vector2D":
    x as Number
    y as Number

Note: 3D Point and Vector Types Type called "Point3D":
    x as Number
    y as Number
    z as Number

Type called "Vector3D":
    x as Number
    y as Number
    z as Number

Note: Basic 2D Shapes
Type called "Line2D":
    start as Point2D
    end as Point2D

Type called "Circle":
    center as Point2D
    radius as Number

Type called "Rectangle":
    x as Number
    y as Number
    width as Number
    height as Number

Type called "Triangle":
    a as Point2D
    b as Point2D
    c as Point2D

Type called "Polygon":
    vertices as List[Point2D]

Note: 3D Shapes
Type called "Sphere":
    center as Point3D
    radius as Number

Type called "Box":
    min_point as Point3D
    max_point as Point3D

Type called "Plane":
    point as Point3D
    normal as Vector3D

Note: Point Operations
Process called "create_point_2d" that takes x as Number and y as Number returns Point2D:
    Return Point2D with:
    x as x
    y as y

Process called "create_point_3d" that takes x as Number and y as Number and z as Number returns Point3D:
    Return Point3D with:
    x as x
    y as y
    z as z

Process called "distance_2d" that takes p1 as Point2D and p2 as Point2D returns Number:
    Let dx be p2.x - p1.x
    Let dy be p2.y - p1.y
    Return Core.sqrt with x as dx * dx dy * dy

Process called "distance_3d" that takes p1 as Point3D and p2 as Point3D returns Number:
    Let dx be p2.x - p1.x
    Let dy be p2.y - p1.y
    Let dz be p2.z - p1.z
    Return Core.sqrt with x as dx * dx dy * dy dz * dz

Process called "midpoint_2d" that takes p1 as Point2D and p2 as Point2D returns Point2D:
    Return Point2D with:
    x as p1.x p2.x / 2
    y as p1.y p2.y / 2

Process called "midpoint_3d" that takes p1 as Point3D and p2 as Point3D returns Point3D:
    Return Point3D with:
    x as p1.x p2.x / 2
    y as p1.y p2.y / 2
    z as p1.z p2.z / 2

Note: Vector Operations
Process called "create_vector_2d" that takes x as Number and y as Number returns Vector2D:
    Return Vector2D with:
    x as x
    y as y

Process called "create_vector_3d" that takes x as Number and y as Number and z as Number returns Vector3D:
    Return Vector3D with:
    x as x
    y as y
    z as z

Process called "vector_from_points_2d" that takes from as Point2D and to as Point2D returns Vector2D:
    Return Vector2D with:
    x as to.x - from.x
    y as to.y - from.y

Process called "vector_from_points_3d" that takes from as Point3D and to as Point3D returns Vector3D:
    Return Vector3D with:
    x as to.x - from.x
    y as to.y - from.y
    z as to.z - from.z

Process called "vector_magnitude_2d" that takes v as Vector2D returns Number:
    Return Core.sqrt with x as v.x * v.x v.y * v.y

Process called "vector_magnitude_3d" that takes v as Vector3D returns Number:
    Return Core.sqrt with x as v.x * v.x v.y * v.y v.z * v.z

Process called "vector_normalize_2d" that takes v as Vector2D returns Vector2D:
    Let magnitude be vector_magnitude_2d with v as v
    If magnitude equals 0:
    Return Vector2D with x as 0 and y as 0
    Return Vector2D with:
    x as v.x / magnitude
    y as v.y / magnitude

Process called "vector_normalize_3d" that takes v as Vector3D returns Vector3D:
    Let magnitude be vector_magnitude_3d with v as v
    If magnitude equals 0:
    Return Vector3D with x as 0 and y as 0 and z as 0
    Return Vector3D with:
    x as v.x / magnitude
    y as v.y / magnitude
    z as v.z / magnitude

Process called "dot_product_2d" that takes v1 as Vector2D and v2 as Vector2D returns Number:
    Return v1.x * v2.x v1.y * v2.y

Process called "dot_product_3d" that takes v1 as Vector3D and v2 as Vector3D returns Number:
    Return v1.x * v2.x v1.y * v2.y v1.z * v2.z

Process called "cross_product_2d" that takes v1 as Vector2D and v2 as Vector2D returns Number:
    Return v1.x * v2.y - v1.y * v2.x

Process called "cross_product_3d" that takes v1 as Vector3D and v2 as Vector3D returns Vector3D:
    Return Vector3D with:
    x as v1.y * v2.z - v1.z * v2.y
    y as v1.z * v2.x - v1.x * v2.z
    z as v1.x * v2.y - v1.y * v2.x

Note: Line Operations
Process called "create_line_2d" that takes start as Point2D and end as Point2D returns Line2D:
    Return Line2D with:
    start as start
    end as end

Process called "line_length_2d" that takes line as Line2D returns Number:
    Return distance_2d with p1 as line.start and p2 as line.end

Process called "line_direction_2d" that takes line as Line2D returns Vector2D:
    Return vector_from_points_2d with from as line.start and to as line.end

Process called "point_on_line_2d" that takes line as Line2D and t as Number returns Point2D:
    Let direction be line_direction_2d with line as line
    Return Point2D with:
    x as line.start.x direction.x * t
    y as line.start.y direction.y * t

Process called "closest_point_on_line_2d" that takes line as Line2D and point as Point2D returns Point2D:
    Let direction be line_direction_2d with line as line
    Let to_point be vector_from_points_2d with from as line.start and to as point
    Let line_length_squared be direction.x * direction.x direction.y * direction.y If line_length_squared equals 0:
    Return line.start Let t be dot_product_2d with v1 as to_point and v2 as direction / line_length_squared
    Set t to Core.clamp with value as t and min_val as 0 and max_val as 1 Return point_on_line_2d with line as line and t as t

Note: Circle Operations
Process called "create_circle" that takes center as Point2D and radius as Number returns Circle:
    Return Circle with:
    center as center
    radius as radius

Process called "circle_area" that takes circle as Circle returns Number:
    Return Core.pi * circle.radius * circle.radius

Process called "circle_circumference" that takes circle as Circle returns Number:
    Return 2 * Core.pi * circle.radius

Process called "point_in_circle" that takes circle as Circle and point as Point2D returns Boolean:
    Let distance_to_center be distance_2d with p1 as circle.center and p2 as point
    Return distance_to_center <= circle.radius

Process called "circles_intersect" that takes c1 as Circle and c2 as Circle returns Boolean:
    Let distance_between_centers be distance_2d with p1 as c1.center and p2 as c2.center
    Return distance_between_centers <= c1.radius c2.radius

Note: Rectangle Operations
Process called "create_rectangle" that takes x as Number and y as Number and width as Number and height as Number returns Rectangle:
    Return Rectangle with:
    x as x
    y as y
    width as width
    height as height

Process called "rectangle_area" that takes rect as Rectangle returns Number:
    Return rect.width * rect.height

Process called "rectangle_perimeter" that takes rect as Rectangle returns Number:
    Return 2 * rect.width rect.height

Process called "point_in_rectangle" that takes rect as Rectangle and point as Point2D returns Boolean:
    Return point.x >= rect.x and
    point.x <= rect.x rect.width and
    point.y >= rect.y and
    point.y <= rect.y rect.height

Process called "rectangles_intersect" that takes r1 as Rectangle and r2 as Rectangle returns Boolean:
    Return r1.x < r2.x r2.width and
    r1.x r1.width > r2.x and
    r1.y < r2.y r2.height and
    r1.y r1.height > r2.y

Note: Triangle Operations
Process called "create_triangle" that takes a as Point2D and b as Point2D and c as Point2D returns Triangle:
    Return Triangle with:
    a as a
    b as b
    c as c

Process called "triangle_area" that takes triangle as Triangle returns Number:
    Let ab_x be triangle.b.x - triangle.a.x
    Let ab_y be triangle.b.y - triangle.a.y
    Let ac_x be triangle.c.x - triangle.a.x
    Let ac_y be triangle.c.y - triangle.a.y
    Return Core.abs with x as ab_x * ac_y - ab_y * ac_x / 2

Process called "triangle_perimeter" that takes triangle as Triangle returns Number:
    Let side_ab be distance_2d with p1 as triangle.a and p2 as triangle.b
    Let side_bc be distance_2d with p1 as triangle.b and p2 as triangle.c
    Let side_ca be distance_2d with p1 as triangle.c and p2 as triangle.a
    Return side_ab side_bc side_ca

Process called "point_in_triangle" that takes triangle as Triangle and point as Point2D returns Boolean:
    Let area_abc be triangle_area with triangle as triangle
    Let area_pab be triangle_area with triangle as create_triangle with a as point and b as triangle.a and c as triangle.b
    Let area_pbc be triangle_area with triangle as create_triangle with a as point and b as triangle.b and c as triangle.c
    Let area_pca be triangle_area with triangle as create_triangle with a as point and b as triangle.c and c as triangle.a Let total_area be area_pab area_pbc area_pca
    Return Core.abs with x as total_area - area_abc < 1e-10

Process called "triangle_centroid" that takes triangle as Triangle returns Point2D:
    Return Point2D with:
    x as triangle.a.x triangle.b.x triangle.c.x / 3
    y as triangle.a.y triangle.b.y triangle.c.y / 3

Note: Polygon Operations
Process called "create_polygon" that takes vertices as List[Point2D] returns Polygon:
    Return Polygon with:
    vertices as vertices

Process called "polygon_area" that takes polygon as Polygon returns Number:
    If List.length with lst as polygon.vertices < 3:
    Return 0 Let area be 0
    Let n be List.length with lst as polygon.vertices For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Let j be i 1 % n
    Set area to area polygon.vertices[i].x * polygon.vertices[j].y
    Set area to area - polygon.vertices[j].x * polygon.vertices[i].y Return Core.abs with x as area / 2

Process called "polygon_perimeter" that takes polygon as Polygon returns Number:
    If List.length with lst as polygon.vertices < 2:
    Return 0 Let perimeter be 0
    Let n be List.length with lst as polygon.vertices For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Let j be i 1 % n
    Set perimeter to perimeter distance_2d with p1 as polygon.vertices[i] and p2 as polygon.vertices[j] Return perimeter

Process called "point_in_polygon" that takes polygon as Polygon and point as Point2D returns Boolean:
    Let n be List.length with lst as polygon.vertices
    If n < 3:
    Return false Let inside be false
    Let j be n - 1 For i from 0 to n - 1:
    If polygon.vertices[i].y > point.y != polygon.vertices[j].y > point.y:
    Let slope be point.x - polygon.vertices[i].x - polygon.vertices[j].x - polygon.vertices[i].x * point.y - polygon.vertices[i].y / polygon.vertices[j].y - polygon.vertices[i].y
    If slope < 0:
    Set inside to not inside
    Set j to i Return inside

Note: 3D Operations
Process called "create_sphere" that takes center as Point3D and radius as Number returns Sphere:
    Return Sphere with:
    center as center
    radius as radius

Process called "sphere_volume" that takes sphere as Sphere returns Number:
    Return 4 / 3 * Core.pi * sphere.radius * sphere.radius * sphere.radius

Process called "sphere_surface_area" that takes sphere as Sphere returns Number:
    Return 4 * Core.pi * sphere.radius * sphere.radius

Process called "point_in_sphere" that takes sphere as Sphere and point as Point3D returns Boolean:
    Let distance_to_center be distance_3d with p1 as sphere.center and p2 as point
    Return distance_to_center <= sphere.radius

Process called "create_box" that takes min_point as Point3D and max_point as Point3D returns Box:
    Return Box with:
    min_point as min_point
    max_point as max_point

Process called "box_volume" that takes box as Box returns Number:
    Let width be box.max_point.x - box.min_point.x
    Let height be box.max_point.y - box.min_point.y
    Let depth be box.max_point.z - box.min_point.z
    Return width * height * depth

Process called "point_in_box" that takes box as Box and point as Point3D returns Boolean:
    Return point.x >= box.min_point.x and
    point.x <= box.max_point.x and
    point.y >= box.min_point.y and
    point.y <= box.max_point.y and
    point.z >= box.min_point.z and
    point.z <= box.max_point.z

Note: Transformations
Process called "translate_point_2d" that takes point as Point2D and dx as Number and dy as Number returns Point2D:
    Return Point2D with:
    x as point.x dx
    y as point.y dy

Process called "rotate_point_2d" that takes point as Point2D and angle as Number and origin as Point2D returns Point2D:
    Let cos_angle be Core.cos with angle as angle
    Let sin_angle be Core.sin with angle as angle
    Let translated_x be point.x - origin.x
    Let translated_y be point.y - origin.y Return Point2D with:
    x as translated_x * cos_angle - translated_y * sin_angle origin.x
    y as translated_x * sin_angle translated_y * cos_angle origin.y

Process called "scale_point_2d" that takes point as Point2D and scale_x as Number and scale_y as Number and origin as Point2D returns Point2D:
    Return Point2D with:
    x as origin.x point.x - origin.x * scale_x
    y as origin.y point.y - origin.y * scale_y

Note: Advanced Geometry
Process called "convex_hull" that takes points as List[Point2D] returns List[Point2D]:
    Let n be List.length with lst as points
    If n < 3:
    Return points Note: Find bottommost point
    Let bottom be 0
    For i from 1 to n - 1:
    If points[i].y < points[bottom].y:
    Set bottom to i
    Otherwise if points[i].y equals points[bottom].y and points[i].x < points[bottom].x:
    Set bottom to i Note: Swap bottom point to first position
    Let temp be points[0]
    Set points[0] to points[bottom]
    Set points[bottom] to temp Note: Sort points by polar angle with respect to bottom point
    Let sorted_points be sort_by_polar_angle with points as points and origin as points[0] Note: Graham scan
    Let hull be List.new
    List.add with lst as hull and item as sorted_points[0]
    List.add with lst as hull and item as sorted_points[1] For i from 2 to n - 1:
    While List.length with lst as hull > 1 and ccw with a as hull[List.length with lst as hull - 2] and b as hull[List.length with lst as hull - 1] and c as sorted_points[i] <= 0:
    List.remove_last with lst as hull
    List.add with lst as hull and item as sorted_points[i] Return hull

Process called "sort_by_polar_angle" that takes points as List[Point2D] and origin as Point2D returns List[Point2D]:
    Note: Simple implementation - in production would use more efficient sorting
    Return points

Process called "ccw" that takes a as Point2D and b as Point2D and c as Point2D returns Number:
    Return a.x * b.y - c.y b.x * c.y - a.y c.x * a.y - b.y

Process called "line_intersection_2d" that takes line1 as Line2D and line2 as Line2D returns Point2D:
    Let x1 be line1.start.x
    Let y1 be line1.start.y
    Let x2 be line1.end.x
    Let y2 be line1.end.y
    Let x3 be line2.start.x
    Let y3 be line2.start.y
    Let x4 be line2.end.x
    Let y4 be line2.end.y Let denominator be x1 - x2 * y3 - y4 - y1 - y2 * x3 - x4 If Core.abs with x as denominator < 1e-10:
    Throw "Lines are parallel or coincident"
    Let t be x1 - x3 * y3 - y4 - y1 - y3 * x3 - x4 / denominator Return Point2D with:
    x as x1 t * x2 - x1
    y as y1 t * y2 - y1

Process called "bezier_curve_point" that takes control_points as List[Point2D] and t as Number returns Point2D:
    Let n be List.length with lst as control_points
    If n equals 1:
    Return control_points[0] Let next_points be List.new
    For i from 0 to n - 2:
    Let interpolated be Point2D with:
    x as 1 - t * control_points[i].x t * control_points[i 1].x
    y as 1 - t * control_points[i].y t * control_points[i 1].y
    List.add with lst as next_points and item as interpolated Return bezier_curve_point with control_points as next_points and t as t